Of interest in relation to this...

I've just been reading the second 2006 issue of the BIS's "Space
Chronicle", this one being the papers from their 2005 "UK Spaceplanes"
symposium.  As you might expect, it's largely historical [I've added
sci.space.history to the Newsgroups header], and in particular there are
several papers on HOTOL.

One very interesting part of the HOTOL papers is the shamefaced admission
that when the HOTOL concept study compared the final design against an
all-rocket SSTO, to their horror they found -- as so many others have in
the past -- that an all-rocket SSTO would be superior!

The supposed advantages of the partly-airbreathing HOTOL engine had slowly
eroded away as the detailed engineering was filled in.  In particular, the
target of a 3.5% payload fraction was missed by a factor of 2, even with
assumed use of "advanced" materials.  "Comparison with a conceptual SSTO
pure rocket vehicle indicated that the same assumptions of material and
vehicle properties would give a better payload fraction."
