&gt;vehicle is that it need not lift the oxygen that it consumes.  But
&gt;unfortunately, the vehicle must still accelerate the oxygen (possibly
&gt;along with a lot of nitrogen)...
">

This is a big problem at high speed, but a relatively minor one at low
speed... that being one of the reasons why HOTOL switched to pure-rocket
mode at Mach 5-6 (the other being growing aerodynamic heating).  Until
then, even the nitrogen actually is useful, because a given amount of
energy produces greater impulse (thrust*time) if it's spread over a larger
amount of reaction mass.

The fundamental problem of (low-speed) airbreathing for SSTOs is not
accelerating the oxygen, but having to handle such a bulky, low-density
oxidizer.  (Air is roughly 1.2kg/m^3 at sea level, and much less at high
altitude; LOX is about 1140kg/m^3 at boiling point.)  The sheer bulk of the
incoming air requires large, heavy machinery, which has to be carried all
the way to orbit.  The complexities of having two different propulsion
systems -- even if they share some hardware -- also add dry mass.  Getting
enough gain from airbreathing to make up for this is challenging.

An important secondary problem is the drag and heating added by flying
low enough to breathe air, rather than getting out of the atmosphere as
quickly as possible.  (Gary Hudson once suggested a rule of thumb:
airbreathing schemes which show an advantage on a traditional vertical
rocket trajectory are worth considering, but changing the trajectory to
make them work better is a lethal mistake.)
