<QUOTE PREVIOUSPOST="
Neil Gerace &lt;gera ... @iinet.net.au&gt; wrote:
&gt;&gt; varying intake area could be simplified if there were provisions to
&gt;&gt; &quot;spill&quot; some of the incoming air into an exhaust duct...

&gt;Concorde also has &quot;spill doors&quot; on the intakes of its Olympus 593s. But they
&gt;act to let air spill *into* the engine at low airspeeds. Is a puzzlement.
">

Those are "suck-in" doors, a somewhat different story.

Efficient operation at supersonic, or even high subsonic, speed tends to
require relatively sharp-edged inlets, to avoid the shock waves that would
form on rounded edges (and the resulting drag).  The trouble is that at
low speed but high power (e.g. takeoff), the engine is taking in a lot of
air and so the flow is converging on the intake from the sides.  With a
sharp-edged intake, that converging flow has to make a relatively tight
turn around the intake lip, and flow separation (with resulting turbulence
and engine problems) is quite likely.

Suck-in doors on the sides of the intake let airflow bypass the intake lip
at low speed, reducing the flow convergence and the tendency to flow
separation.  (The Harrier has particularly conspicuous suck-in doors.)
They're a particularly elegant solution because the pressure differences
between inside and outside automatically hold them closed or open as
required -- they don't even need springs!

People have also experimented with variable-geometry intake lips and such.
The original B-1 had intakes that enlarged for takeoff and landing --
suck-in doors were problematic because the intakes are quite near the
landing gear, and debris thrown up could have been inhaled -- although I
don't remember whether this was retained when the intakes were later
simplified.

Real, true spill doors -- aka bypass ducts -- are found in the intakes of
some high-speed aircraft, e.g. the Blackbirds.  Normally the engine will
inhale only what it needs, with the remainder of the flow turning outward
to avoid the intake (the reverse of the low-speed convergence), but this
flow turning can itself cause problems, especially at supersonic speed,
and it can sometimes be better to inhale extra air and bypass it around
the engine, even though this adds complexity and some drag.

(Jet-engine air intakes are a much more complicated subject than you might
at first think.)
